<paragraph blockId="21.[826,1442,196,493]" box="[826,935,196,217]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis box="[826,935,196,217]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[826,1442,196,493]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
Endoantennal conglobation. Very small: maximum 
<quantity box="[826,914,257,279]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
. Integument smooth, with very fine and short ‘hairs’. Eye reduced, represented only by a spot of pigment without lens, or entirely absent. Cephalothorax rounded, without any rectangular corner. Pleotelson rounded, with straight sides. Flagellum of second antenna three-jointed, and very slender. All coxal plates simple. Noduli laterales small, on the hind margins of the tergites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[826,1442,554,638]" box="[826,913,554,575]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis box="[826,913,554,575]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Remark</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[826,1442,554,638]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<bibRefCitation author="Vandel A" box="[826,991,585,607]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="147 - 172" refId="ref84162" refString="Vandel A. 1972. Les isopodes terrestres de la Colombie. Studies on the Neotropical Fauna 7: 147 - 172." type="journal article" year="1972">Vandel (1972)</bibRefCitation>
defined this genus by its ‘numerous regressive traits’.
</paragraph>
